splash.splashContent:
Welcome to our web app!



This app displays relevant economic and health-related data to determine vulnerable neighbourhoods in the City of Toronto during the ongoing COVID-19 pandemic. This information can help to inform important decisions regarding resource allocation, new locations for assessment centers or drive-thru testing, etc.

To help you navigate this web app and its tools, start by clicking the information icon located in the top left side bar of your screen!

In this web app, the following layers of data are provided:
  • A weighted assessment of vulnerability based on health factors
  • A weighted assessment of vulnerability based on economic factors
  • All standardized layers used in the assessment
Disclaimer: The COVID-19 pandemic is an extremely dynamic situation. Assessment center locations are up-to-date as of March 25th, 2020.The data used in this web app was derived from the 2014 reference period and the most recent 2016 census. Additionally, the manner in which the data was weighted was up to the discretion of the app creators but these decisions have been informed by research articles and reputable sources such as the World Health Organization and Centers for Disease Control and Prevention.


App created by: MapMasters, McMaster University
Esri Canada Centre of Excellence App Challenge 2020

about.aboutContent:
For In-Panel Tools (located along the left side bar)

Layer List

  • Use this tool to toggle on/off the other informational layers displayed on the map.
  • Visible layers higher up in the list will be displayed on top of those that are lower.
  • Click on the more options icon beside each layer name to open more options such as moving layers up/down or viewing its attribute table.
Hint: Check out the locations of hospitals and existing COVID-19 assessment centers throughout the city.
- Feel free to click on each location for a pop-up containing useful information!

Legend

  • Use this tool to view the legends of visible layers on the map.

Bookmarks

  • Use this tool to view pre-set extents of the map.
  • Feel free to create your own bookmarks for areas by positioning the extent of the map in your area of interest, then click the "Add" button located at the top of the widget and name your bookmark!
Hint: Use the search bar to help display your area of interest on the map.

Print

  • Use this tool to export and save your map as multiple formats including PDFs.
  • Click on the "Advanced Settings" button to adjust other parameters such as print quality (DPI).

Share

  • Use this tool to share this web app on social media (e.g. Twitter, Facebook, etc.) or to embed this web app in another site.

For On-Screen Tools (located at the top left corner)

Vulnerability Summary


  • This tool gives the user a summary of the two susceptibility analysis maps based on economic and health-related factors. Users will be able to see the neighbourhoods organized into categories of vulnerability based on a pairwise comparison calculation.
  • Once you open the tool, choose which vulnerability data (health or economic) by clicking the circle icon.
  • Next, select what vulnerability level you are interested in to see all the Toronto neighbourhoods (organized by alphabetical order) in that category.
  • To see more information for a specific neighbourhood, click on its name which will bring up a pop-up including the population, vulnerability values and all the other values of this neighbourhood that contributed to its vulnerability assessment.

Custom Assessment


  • If the user does not want to use the provided susceptibility assessment layers, this tool allows the user to identify susceptible neighbourhoods according to their own criteria. This can be useful when determining where to allocate food, funds, or medical resources based on specific values that the user may be interested in.
  • First, make sure that the Neighbourhood layer is displayed on the map.
  • Next, click the Custom Assessment tool to display a selection of four filters. Within each economic and health factor category, users are able to filter based on either rates (per 1000 people) or absolute counts.
  • Once the desired values are entered, users can view the neighbourhoods that fit their criteria.
  • To restore the map to its initial state, click the "Reset filters" button to remove the filter and any inputted values. To turn off all filters, click the "Turn off filters" button. Both of these are accessible by clicking the more options icon.

Compare


  • This tool allows the user to quickly and easily visualize the difference between two factors of interest.
  • To use the Compare tool, select the two layers you want to compare in the Layer List. Then click on the Compare tool icon.
  • Make sure that only the topmost box in the drop-down menu is selected.
  • Then drag the slider across the map to view the differences.
  • Note: If the layer you are viewing is hidden by upper layers, the Compare tool won't have an effect.
